Here's a typical `MauiProgram.cs` setup:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;

public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Services
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `DataService` | **Singleton** | Holds an `HttpClient` and shared state (cache, auth tokens). One instance avoids socket exhaustion and keeps state consistent app-wide. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation creates a fresh VM with clean state — no stale data leaking between visits. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Matches the VMs. A new page instance per navigation avoids UI state bugs (old list selections, scroll positions, etc.). |

**Key rules of thumb:**

- **Singleton** — stateful services shared everywhere (HTTP clients, caches, settings).
- **Transient** — pages and ViewModels so each navigation gets a fresh instance.
- **Scoped** — rarely used in MAUI (no per-request scope like ASP.NET), but useful if you create your own scopes for workflows.

> ⚠️ Never inject a **Transient** or **Scoped** service into a **Singleton** — the shorter-lived service becomes a de-facto singleton and won't be garbage collected.
